Introduction

This notebook will go through the pipeline that led to the data exports for DAVID.

Note that most linked GitHub repos are currently private. Email me for access.

This pipe was developed in many different parts, but I will attempt to consolidate all the code snippets and tools that led to the most current iteration of the pipe, starting from downloading the data from the genomics core, to getting feature counts from RNASeq Alignment, to cleaning up the featurecounts data in python, to finding oscillating genes on Midway, to subsetting data from eJTK for DAVID in R. Linked are the original code locations.

A note about the many repos:

  • RNA-SEQualizer is the main repo for all analysis not run on the Midway server.
  • RNASeqAlign is the repo on Midway for running STAR alignment + featurecounts.
  • eJTK is the repo on Midway for running eJTK_CYCLE.

Below is the current file structure of the main repository, only listing the relevant files referenced in this document. For the sake of integrity, this notebook will work independently of the rest of the file structures, and will only pull eJTK outputs and DAVID.py. If running in RStudio, the only code that can be run locally is after eJTK outputs; everything before is only presented for documentation purposes.

Obtaining data

Data was obtained from the Genomics core as FASTQ files.
On the genomics core website, the files are:

/
│
├─190715_K00242_0584_AH7GWCBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-2lns     # 7/23/19, 2 lanes
├─191002_K00242_0622_AHF3VKBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-ln2      # 10/3/19, 1 lane
├─191004_K00242_0623_AHF5CTBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-lns456   # 10/7/19, 3 lanes

There are a total of 6 lanes.
Data was downloaded to the Lab Mac, where data prep was run. The folders remained in the above file structure to run the data prep below.

Data prep

Data prep was to join all lanes into a single file for each sample, and have each of these files in its own folder. This was accomplished using 3 scripts. FileEdits1.py renamed all fastq.gz files in the working directory to a simpler name - “initials_samplenumber_lanenumber.fastq.gz”. The script depends on the files following the correct order for renaming. This can be checked by running sorted(glob.glob('*.fastq.gz')) in the directory, which should output a list with the correct order of files (order of increasing lanes, increasing sample numbers). FileEdits2.py takes all the renamed files and sorts them into individual folders for each sample, containing all lanes for that sample. concatenate.sh concatenates all lanes into a single file.

I will show the scripts, along with the expected file structures at each stage.

Before running the script, the number of lanes in the current folder, the lane to start relabeling with, and the total number of lanes must be updated in the scripts. See the comments in the scripts.

FileEdits1.py is run in each folder downloaded from genomics core separately. For example, it was first run like this:

/
│
├─190715_K00242_0584_AH7GWCBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-2lns/
│ ├─FileEdits1.py
│ ├─*.fastq.gz                                      # all fastq.gz files for this RNA Seq run
├─191002_K00242_0622_AHF3VKBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-ln2/
├─191004_K00242_0623_AHF5CTBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-lns456/

Then, like this:

/
│
├─190715_K00242_0584_AH7GWCBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-2lns/
├─191002_K00242_0622_AHF3VKBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-ln2/
│ ├─FileEdits1.py
│ ├─*.fastq.gz                                      # all fastq.gz files for this RNA Seq run
├─191004_K00242_0623_AHF5CTBBXY-EC-KF-RS72-lns456/

FileEdits1.py 
#!/usr/bin/env python

import os
import glob
import shutil
import sys

files = sorted(glob.glob('*.fastq.gz'))

initials = "KF" # Change to your initials
lanes = 2       # Change depending on the number of lanes in the current directory.
l_start = 2     # Change to the first lane in to begin relabeling with. E.g. if there are 3 lanes, lanes 4, 5, & 6, then this should be set to 4.
new_names = []

for i in range(int(len(files)/lanes)):
    if i < 9:
        for j in range(lanes):
            new_names.append(initials + '_S0' + str(i+1) + '_L' + str(j+l_start) + '.fastq.gz')
    else:
        for j in range(lanes):
            new_names.append(initials + '_S' + str(i+1) + '_L' + str(j+l_start) + '.fastq.gz')

if len(new_names) != len(files):    # should be true to proceed to renaming
    sys.exit('generating new names failed')

i = 0
for file in sorted(glob.glob('*.fastq.gz')):
    os.rename(file, new_names[i])
    i += 1

The file structure will be unchanged. The files will simply all be renamed. They can then be moved into one central folder, as such:

/
│
├─FileEdits2.py
├─*.fastq.gz                                        # all fastq.gz files from all folders

FileEdits2.py 
#!/usr/bin/env python

import os
import glob
import shutil

files = sorted(glob.glob('*.fastq.gz'))
total_lanes = 6     # Change to the total number of lanes in the directory

def makedirectory(dirname):
    if not os.path.exists(dirname):    # Make output directory if it doesn't exist
        os.makedirs(dirname)

k = 0
for i in range(1,73):
    for j in range(total_lanes):
        if i < 10:
            dir = '0' + str(i)
            makedirectory(dir)
            shutil.move(files[k], dir + '/' + files[k])
        else:
            dir = str(i)
            makedirectory(dir)
            shutil.move(files[k], dir + '/' + files[k])
        k += 1

Lanes can then be concatenated into single files using a bash script concatenate.sh. It parses through all folders and joins all fastq.gz files into one file.


concatenate.sh 
#!/bin/bash

for d in */
do
    cd "$d"
    for i in *.fastq.gz
    do
        cat "$i" >> KF_S${d:0:2}.fastq.gz && rm "$i" || break   # Change 'KF' to your initials
    done
    cd ..
done

Troubleshooting

Any references to “KF” should be replaced with the correct initials for the experiment.
FileEdit2.py and concatenate.sh only need to be run once, but FileEdit1.py needs to be manually edited and run in every directory.
FileEdit2.py requires all files to be in a working folder from which the script is run.

STAR Alignment

useful link

Alignment was done on the Midway server at /project2/ebchang/Yoyo/RNASeqAlign. There are two steps, alignment then featurecount generation.

Dependencies

The only code dependencies lie with get_queue.py, which requires python==3.6.8 with numpy==1.17.2 and pandas==0.25.2. These can be installed in a conda environment locally on Midway using conda. Remember that base env in Midway is python 2.7, not python 3.7.

Beyond that, the reference genome must be in a folder in working directory called genomeDir.

File structure:

/
│

├─genomeDir/                        # place genome here
├─align_STAR_KF.sbatch
├─parallel_align_STAR_KF.sh
├─get_queue.py

Check code comments for important notices.

Alignment

There are three scripts put together that run the alignment.

align_STAR_KF.sbatch            # Runs the alignment for the individual files

parallel_align_STAR_KF.sbatch   # A shell wrapper for align_STAR_KF.sbatch to run multiple alignments at a time

get_queue.py                    # Python script to prevent running too many files at once and getting banned from Midway

#!/bin/sh

#--------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Bash script to run 'align_STAR.sbatch' in parallel
# I couldn't figure out how to stop running after a certain amount of jobs
# Please only run 10 max in parallel (keep in separate folders?)

#--------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Edit Yoyo 10/2019
# Goes through every folder in the data folder (${fastq_dir}) to find fastq.gz and load those into sbatch files to run on server.
# Assumes there are about 10 files per folder in the data folder, and no fastq.gz files are outside of folders.

for FOLDER in */

    cd ${FOLDER}

        do
        cd ${star_dir}
    pathfile2=${fastq_dir}${FOLDER}
    pathfile=${fastq_dir}${FOLDER}${FILE}
    errfile="${fastq_dir}${FOLDER}errors/${FILE%%.*}"

    echo "FOLDER"
    echo ${FOLDER}
    echo "FILE"
    echo ${FILE}

    # echo "pathfile2"
    # echo ${pathfile2}
    # echo "pathfile"
    # echo ${pathfile}
    # echo "errfile"
    # echo ${errfile}

    mkdir ${fastq_dir}${FOLDER}errors/ 
    sed -i "4,5 s|VARIABLE|${errfile}|g" ${batchfile}
    sed -i "28 s|VARIABLE|${pathfile}|g" ${batchfile}
        sed -i "29 s|VARIABLE|${pathfile2}|g" ${batchfile}
    # sbatch ${batchfile}   # UNCOMMENT TO SUBMIT JOBS TO MIDWAY. MAKE SURE SCRIPTS WORK AS INTENDED FIRST.
    sed -i "s|${errfile}|VARIABLE|g" ${batchfile}
    sed -i "s|${pathfile}|VARIABLE|g" ${batchfile}
    sed -i "s|${pathfile2}|VARIABLE|g" ${batchfile}
    python get_queue.py
    done
    cd $fastq_dir
done

get_queue.py 
#!/usr/bin/env python

import subprocess
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from io import StringIO
import time

name = 'smanzoor'   # Change this to your rcc username

while True:
    process = subprocess.Popen(['squeue','--user=' + name], stdout=subprocess.PIPE, universal_newlines=True)

    f = process.stdout.read()
    f = f.replace('\n', 'slashn')
    f = ' '.join(f.split())
    f = f.replace('slashn','\n')
    f = StringIO(unicode(f))

    df = pd.read_csv(f, sep=' ')
    df = df.reset_index(drop=True)

    time.sleep(5)
    if len(df.index) < 2:
        break
    elif len(df.index) == 0:
        break

Toubleshooting

Files are expected to be gunzip’d. If they remain .gz before running, use command --readFilesIn zcat. See STAR manual.
get_queue.py depends on squeue --user to output a table. If the code breaks, RCC may have changed formatting of the squeue output.
Also, sed in parallel_align_STAR_KF.sbatch calls specific lines in align_STAR_KF.sbatch, so that may be a source of breaking.

Prepping data for eJTK

Dependencies

  • python==3.7
  • numpy
  • pandas
  • feather (optional, if not used, gene expression data filepaths may need to be updated from .feather to .csv in downstream scripts)

Code

Data was prepared in python. It makes several assumptions of the experimental setup to work: - There are the same number of replicates for each condition at each time period - The time between replicates is consistent for the entire experiment

This file also swaps the data for KF_17 and KF_21.


RNA Seq Counts Data Processing.py 
import os
from io import StringIO
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import feather as ft
from File_Export import *

data = 'KF_RNAseq_counts.txt'
number_of_conditions = 4    # number of conditions in the experiment
timepoints = 6              # total number of time points in the experiment
t_d = 4                     # amount of time between each time point (in hours)
initial_time = 2            # initial time (Zeitgeber time) that the experiment starts

directory = 'data'
if not os.path.exists(directory):    # Make output directory if it doesn't exist
    os.makedirs(directory)

def write_dataset_to_file(dataframe, filename, directory=directory):
    filename = directory + '/%s' % filename
    filepath = '%s.feather' % filename
    ft.write_dataframe(dataframe, filepath)    # write to feather
    # filepath = '%s.csv' % filename
    # dataframe.to_csv(filepath, sep='\t',index=False)    # write to csv

def write_dataset_to_txt(dataframe, filename, directory=directory):
    """function to write datasets to csv. Datasets are saved in directory"""
    filename = directory + '/%s' % filename
    filepath = '%s.txt' % filename
    dataframe.to_csv(filepath, sep=' ', index=None)    # write to txt

f = open(data, 'r').read()
f = f.split('\n', 1)[1]

# Read in data frame from string (converted to filetype using StringIO)
df = pd.read_csv(StringIO(f), sep='\t', header=0)
# Remove Chr, Start, End, Strand, and Length columns (columns 1-5, indexed 1:6).
# Output dataframe:
#   0   | 1 | 2 | 3...
# ------|---|---|---
#  Gene | counts
df = df.drop(df.columns[1:6], axis=1)

# Make a list that will take the names from the file path name. This is done by splitting files by '/' then selecting the 6th element, which is 'KF_(some integer)'.
# Example file path: /project2/ebchang/Katya/ML_analysis/STAR_alignment/KF_46/KF_46_Aligned.sortedByCoord.out.bam
col_names = ['Geneid']    # define list, already containing the first column so the dimensions will be the same as the dataframe
for i in list(df):
    if i == 'Geneid':    # I don't want the column that contains Gene ids
        next
    else:
        label = i.split('/')[6]
        col_names.append(label)

df.columns = col_names

# Making labels to reorder the dataframe to be, like, actually sensible
new_order = ['Geneid']
for i in range(0,(len(df.columns)-1)):
    k = i+1
    if k < 10:
        new_order.append(label.split('_')[0] + '_0%s' % k)    # To align with already existing column names, which have '01'-'09' as opposed to '1'-'9'
    else:
        new_order.append(label.split('_')[0] + '_%s' % k)

df = df.reindex(columns=new_order)

# Swap column a with column b, in this case KF_17 with KF_21
a = 'KF_17'
b = 'KF_21'
df['temp'] = df[a]
df[a] = df[b]
df[b] = df['temp']
df = df.drop('temp', axis=1)

# Remove rows that have 0s only (ignores first column, gene id)
df = df.loc[(df[df.columns[1:]]!=0).any(axis=1)]

# Gets col names as needed in eJTK
def get_col_names(dataframe,samples_per_condition,timepoints,initial_time,delta_time):
    col_names = ['#']    # initialize columns with first column as '#'
    for i in range(len(list(dataframe))-1):    # iterate through every column, ignoring Gene id
        if not i % samples_per_condition:    # filter to only take # of samples/conditions to iterate through
            for k in range(timepoints):    # iterate for the entire time
                time = (delta_time*k)+initial_time
                ztime = 'ZT%s' % time
                for j in range(int(samples_per_condition/timepoints)):    # iterate for each sample measured within a timepoint
                    col_names.append(ztime)
    return col_names

def select_data(dataframe,number_of_conditions,samples_per_condition, method="NA"):
    selected_data = {}
    for i in range(number_of_conditions):
        k = i+1
        start = (samples_per_condition*i)+1
        end = (samples_per_condition*k)+1
        t = dataframe.iloc[:,start:end]
        if method == "eJTK":
            t.insert(0,'#',dataframe['#'])
        else:
            t.insert(0,'Geneid',dataframe['Geneid'])
        selected_data[i] = t
    return selected_data

sample_per_condition = int((len(list(df))-1)/number_of_conditions)    # divides number of samples by number of conditions

df_zt = df.copy()

df_zt.columns = get_col_names(df_zt,sample_per_condition,timepoints,initial_time,t_d)

selected_data = select_data(df_zt,number_of_conditions,sample_per_condition, method="eJTK")

# Export eJTK dataframes
file = ['WT_SPF','KO_SPF','WT_GF','KO_GF']
for i in range(len(file)):
    write_dataset_to_txt(selected_data[i], file[i])    # feather will not accept duplicate column names :(

dict_separate_conditions = select_data(df_zt,number_of_conditions,sample_per_condition)    # df output with log transformations

# Export transformed Circadian dataframes
file = ['R/WT_SPF_R','R/KO_SPF_R','R/WT_GF_R','R/KO_GF_R']
for i in range(len(file)):
    write_dataset_to_file(dict_separate_conditions[i], file[i])

This results in 4 files, ‘WT_SPF.txt’, ‘KO_SPF.txt’, ‘WT_GF.txt’, ‘KO_GF.txt’, in a data/ folder that are curated for eJTK analysis, and 4 .feather files in a data/R/ folder that are generated for use in graphing later.

parallel_eJTK.sh 
#!/bin/bash

wdir="/project2/ebchang/Yoyo/eJTK"
batchfile="${wdir}/run_eJTK.sbatch"

cd ${wdir}/data
for FILE in *.txt
do
    echo "Running ${FILE%%.*}"
    cd ${wdir}
    sed -i "s/VARIABLE/${FILE}/g" ${batchfile}
    sbatch ${batchfile}
    sed -i "s/${FILE}/VARIABLE/g" ${batchfile}
    sleep 1
done

Running eJTK

Recommended to keep a copy of the original data in a folder not in data, and copy them into the data folder every time eJTK is run. When I ran this, I took the 4 text outputs from the python scripts prior.

  1. python environment must be activated
  2. clear data and LOGS via rm data/* LOGS/*
  3. place your data into the data folder (do not load more than 10 items in the data folder)
  4. if not done yet, make parallel_eJTK.sh executable via chmod +x parallel_eJTK.sh
  5. run by command ./parallel_eJTK.sh

Files are outputted into the data/ folder. The only needed output ends with jtkout_GammaP.

Visualization

Venn diagram

The sets can be visualized in a Venn diagram. dataCombinations is a basic data structure to hold all levels of the diagram.

# Put all combinations into one list
# 1 = WT SPF
# 2 = KO SPF
# 3 = WT GF
# 4 = KO GF
# n = intersect
# d = difference (in the first element, not in the second)
# d_a = difference between first element and all other groups
dataCombinations <- list(
  WT_SPF,
  KO_SPF,
  WT_GF,
  KO_GF,
  inner_join(WT_SPF,KO_SPF),
  inner_join(WT_SPF,WT_GF),
  inner_join(WT_SPF,KO_GF),
  inner_join(KO_SPF,WT_GF),
  inner_join(KO_SPF,KO_GF),
  inner_join(WT_GF,KO_GF),
  Reduce(inner_join, list(WT_SPF,KO_SPF,WT_GF)),
  Reduce(inner_join, list(WT_SPF,KO_SPF,KO_GF)),
  Reduce(inner_join, list(WT_SPF,WT_GF,KO_GF)),
  Reduce(inner_join, list(KO_SPF,WT_GF,KO_GF)),
  Reduce(inner_join, list(WT_SPF,KO_SPF,WT_GF,KO_GF)),
  setdiff(WT_SPF$ID, KO_SPF$ID),
  setdiff(KO_SPF$ID, WT_SPF$ID),
  setdiff(WT_SPF$ID, WT_GF$ID),
  setdiff(WT_GF$ID, WT_SPF$ID),
  setdiff(KO_SPF$ID, KO_GF$ID),
  setdiff(KO_GF$ID, KO_SPF$ID),
  setdiff(WT_GF$ID, KO_GF$ID),
  setdiff(KO_GF$ID, WT_GF$ID),
  Reduce(setdiff, list(WT_SPF$ID, KO_SPF$ID, WT_GF$ID, KO_GF$ID)),
  Reduce(setdiff, list(KO_SPF$ID, WT_SPF$ID, WT_GF$ID, KO_GF$ID)),
  Reduce(setdiff, list(WT_GF$ID, WT_SPF$ID, KO_SPF$ID, KO_GF$ID)),
  Reduce(setdiff, list(KO_GF$ID, WT_SPF$ID, KO_SPF$ID, WT_GF$ID))
) %>%

List sets

Overview

The data can be imagined as sets.

  • Let \(\text{WT}_U\) be the set of all wild-type mice.
  • Let \(\text{KO}_U\) be the set of all L-Bmal1-KO mice.
  • Let \(\text{SPF}_U\) be the set of all specific pathogen free mice.

  • Let \(\text{GF}_U\) be the set of all germ-free mice.

  • Let \(WT\_SPF\) be the set of all genes \(g\) such that \(\{\,g \in WT\_SPF \mid g \in (\text{WT}_U \wedge \text{SPF}_U ) \wedge g \text{ is oscillating}\,\}\).
  • Let \(KO\_SPF\) be the set of all genes \(g\) such that \(\{\,g \in KO\_SPF \mid g \in (\text{KO}_U \wedge \text{SPF}_U ) \wedge g \text{ is oscillating}\,\}\).
  • Let \(WT\_GF\) be the set of all genes \(g\) such that \(\{\,g \in WT\_GF \mid g \in (\text{WT}_U \wedge \text{GF}_U ) \wedge g \text{ is oscillating}\,\}\).

  • Let \(KO\_GF\) be the set of all genes \(g\) such that \(\{\,g \in KO\_GF \mid g \in (\text{KO}_U \wedge \text{GF}_U ) \wedge g \text{ is oscillating}\,\}\).

Possible subsetted sets from each of the above sets can be interpreted in interesting ways in terms of pathway results from DAVID, e.g. the pathways that are oscillating in WT SPF mice, but not in their L-Bmal1-KO SPF counterparts, or pathways that are circadian in the SPF condition but not the GF condition, or pathways that are oscillating no matter the perturbation.

Setup

Using reticulate, a python source with pandas is needed.

Some python functions are sourced in DAVID.py.

source_python("../py/DAVID.py")

Below is the the python source code.


DAVID.py 
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

def unique_in_x_groups(df, colname, *args):
    """
    colname = the name of the column that will be compared between groups. Must be the same colname in all dataframes or else it will be skipped.
    df = dataframe being analyzed for uniques
    *args = dataframes being compared to df
    """
    totalList = pd.concat([x[colname] for x in args]).drop_duplicates().reset_index(drop=True)
    return([x for x in df[colname] if x not in totalList.tolist()])

def combine_x_groups(colname, *args):
    """
    returns a combination of all dataframes in *args. Colname must be the same in all dataframes.
    """
    return(pd.concat([x[colname] for x in args]).drop_duplicates().reset_index(drop=True))

genotype_unique and microbe_unique

genetype_unique are the sets:

  • \((WT\_SPF \cap WT\_GF)^\mathsf{c}\)
  • \((KO\_SPF \cap KO\_GF)^\mathsf{c}\)
graphic of \((WT\_SPF \cap WT\_GF)^\mathsf{c}\)

microbe_unique are the sets:

  • \((WT\_SPF \cap KO\_SPF)^\mathsf{c}\)
  • \((WT\_GF \cap KO\_GF)^\mathsf{c}\)
graphic of \((KO\_SPF \cap KO\_GF)^\mathsf{c}\)

Since P values are assigned based on the first 4 sets, that is, \(WT\_SPF\), \(KO\_SPF\), \(WT\_GF\), and \(KO\_GF\), the above 4 sets can’t be made as 4 individual lists without many nonoverlapping genes.

Let \(p_1\) be the p values given to all genes \(g\) in the set \(WT\_SPF\) such that \(\exists\, p_1 \,(\,\forall\, g \in WT\_SPF)\).
Let \(p_2\) be the p values given to all genes \(g\) in the set \(KO\_SPF\) such that \(\exists\, p_1 \,(\,\forall\, g \in KO\_SPF)\).
Assume all genes are not unique, but all p values are unique.
Since \(WT\_SPF \ncong KO\_SPF\),
\(\neg\,\exists\, g \,(\,\forall\, p \in p_1 \cup p_2)\)

Thus, there will be 8 lists:

  • \(WT\_SPF - WT\_GF\) # WT_1 view
  • \(WT\_GF - WT\_SPF\) # WT_2 view
  • \(KO\_SPF - KO\_GF\) # KO_1 view

  • \(KO\_GF - KO\_SPF\) # KO_2 view

  • \(WT\_SPF - KO\_SPF\) # SPF_1 view
  • \(KO\_SPF - WT\_SPF\) # SPF_2 view
  • \(WT\_GF - KO\_GF\) # GF_1 view

  • \(KO\_GF - WT\_GF\) # GF_2 view

These are equivalent, e.g \(((WT\_SPF - WT\_GF) \cup WT\_GF - WT\_SPF) \cong (WT\_SPF \cap WT\_GF)^\mathsf{c}\)
